value.value: An anatomical plane that bisects a zone of weakness in an appendage. When autotamy occurs, the appendage divides along this plane.
A plane of autotomy that divides an appendage through a bone.
A plane of autotomy that divides an appendage through a vertebral bone.
A plane of autotomy that divides an appendage in the space between appendage bones.

label.value: plane of autotomy bisecting intervertebral joint

value.value: A plane of autotomy that divides an appendage in the space between vertebrae.
A post-anal tail that attaches outside the tail.
A muscle that originates via thin tendons from the proximal and dorsal aspects of the neural spines and inserts via fleshy fibers onto the lateral aspect of the base of the neural arch.

A muscle that originates via thin tendons from the distal and dorsal aspects of the neural spines. The tendons course proximomedially to distolaterally and give rise to fleshy fibers that insert onto the lateral aspect of the neural arches of each of the vertebrae it crosses. The m. extensor caudae medialis is a continuation of m. semispinalis dorsi into the tail.

A muscle that originates via a robust tendon from a tuberosity on the cranial aspect of the iliac crest and via fleshy fibers from the caudoventral aspect of the pelvis, the lateral aspects of the transverse processes of Ca2-8 or 9, and the horizontal intramuscular septum.
A muscle that attaches to the iliac crest and to a caudal vertebra.
A muscle that overlies the hemipenis.
A muscle in females that overlies the soft tissue related to the cloaca, where the hemipenes are located in males.
A tube-like muscle attaches to the distal tip of the hemipenis and inserts onto the transverse processes of a caudal vertebra.
A transverse process that is part of a caudal vertebra.

label.value: perineal body smooth muscle muscle tissue

value.value: Any of the two testis-carrying compartments of the scrotum.
The perineal raphe extends from the anus, through the mid-line of the scrotum (scrotal raphe) and upwards through the posterior mid-line aspect of the penis (penile raphe).

The temporal fascia covers the Temporalis muscle. It is a strong, fibrous investment, covered, laterally, by the Auricularis anterior and superior, by the galea aponeurotica, and by part of the Orbicularis oculi. The superficial temporal vessels and the auriculotemporal nerve cross it from below upward. Above, it is a single layer, attached to the entire extent of the superior temporal line; but below, where it is fixed to the zygomatic arch, it consists of two layers, one of which is inserted into the lateral, and the other into the medial border of the arch. A small quantity of fat, the orbital branch of the superficial temporal artery, and a filament from the zygomatic branch of the maxillary nerve, are contained between these two layers. It affords attachment by its deep surface to the superficial fibers of the Temporalis.

definition.value: Request new term but the definition needs revision.

value.value: A nerve that innervates the sole of the foot. Planar nerves arise from the posterior branch of the tibial nerve.

definition.value: Divided into medial and plantar based on the location of the foot supplied

value.value: A plantar nerve that supplies the lateral side of the plantar part of the foot, including pedal digit 5.
A plantar nerve that supplies the medial side of the plantar part of the foot, including pedal digit 1.
Any of the muscles that are entirely within the body part or segment moved by them.

label.value: central part of mediodorsal nucleus of the thalamus
lateral part of mediodorsal nucleus of the thalamus

value.value: A space or gap between the left and right central incisors, on either the upper or lower jaw.
A space or gap between the left and right central incisors on the upper jaw.
A space or gap between the left and right central incisors on the lower jaw.

Any material entity that is located in the digestive tract. This includes undigested food and liquid as well as unexcreted waste products. It also includes other entities such as ingested stones used to aid digestion. Any microbial cells or cell populations are also included.
A space or gap any two incisors. This may be a midline diastema between central incisors, or a diastema located entirely in a single jaw quadrant between lateral incisors.
Lateral walls of the oropharynx that are located medial to the palatoglossal folds.
Median palatine suture of the palatine processes of the maxillary bones, and the median suture of the palatine bones.
Line of union, in the floor of the orbit, between the orbital process of the palatine bone and the orbital surface of the maxilla.
A line of junction of the orbital process of the palatine bone and the orbital plate of the ethmoid.
The line of junction between the processes of the maxilla and the horizontal parts of the palatine bones that form the hard palate.
Any of the sutures of the hard palate.
A curved region of the skeleton of the pes (foot) formed by the tarsal and metatarsal bones.
A pointed projection at the front extremity of the intermaxillary suture.
Space between the prepuce and glans penis or clitoris.
